Please generate a CLI tool `compdir` using Rust. It accepts either 2 (left and right) or 1 (right) arguments. (Except for -h, --help which
  shows a brief synopsis and exist).
  Each of these arguments are of shape 'path' or 'host:path' or 'host:'
  If there is only one argument treat it like the second argument (right) and use current dir path for the first argument (left).
  Subsequently if one of the arguments is of shape 'host:' and the other is of shape 'path' then use 'host:path' path (resolve full path first)
  instead of 'host:' shape. If both arguments are of shape 'host:' then use 'host:$(pwd)' instead
  Use ssh to access hosts.
 
  The program recursively scans left and right arguments directories and constructs two lists of directories inside (recursively) for each side
  left and right - we are only interested in directories. They should contain *relative paths* to the comparison roots (i.e. L/R argument dirs).
  These lists should actually be hash or ordered tree sets probably - in fact, we remove the same relative paths from both lists and are only
  interested in paths that are not in the opposite directory tree.
 
  Subsequently we construct an ordered tree map. The keys are all the basenames (final path parts of the relative paths) of both lists. The
  values are sorted lists of pairs of shape '(left or right enum, relative_path)'; sorting here means lexicografically - first we have left
  sorted paths, then right sorted paths that correspond to the given basename.
 
  Finally, we use this tree map to construct the output: blank line separated blocks of shape for instance:
  ```
  my-dir
  L a/b/my-dir
  L c/d/e/my-dir
  R a/b/my-dir
  R x/my-dir
  R z/w/s/my-dir
 
  my-dir2
  L mydir2
 
  ```
  (L refers to the left or first argument and R to the right or second argument relative path trees)